  • Attach the slotted top piece to the handle. You may want to use some glue, but it's not required.
  • Thread a rubber band through the two small slots and knot it
  • Wrap the rubber band around a business card at about a third of the way in
  • Pull the rubber band back so that it lines up with the pointed end of the gun
  • Make sure you don't point at anyone's eyes!
  • Let go of the rubber band to fire!

description.text:
This will fix the broken lifter mount on a very common type of sorting rubbish bin (aka trash can).

These bins have been sold globally under numerous brands eg "Crofton" (Aldi), "Kmart", "Walmart" etc.

The arm attachment was poorly engineered with only a few mm of plastic to hold the lid in place.

"never attribute to malice what can be explained by incompetence"

Let's just hope the designer was having a bad day...

Installation

Installation is simply:

  1. Print the piece(s).
  2. Grind or cut off the old mount attachment. I used a Dremel, but a carpet knife should work.
  3. Attach the new mount(s) and glue into place with a permanent adhesive.
  4. Enjoy.

I love japanese Yakitoris and especially the one composed of cheese and beef. So i have created a mold that enables you to cook as you eat in a japanese restaurant. Made of PET (food-compatible), this one is very simple to use: put the beef part (i use carpaccio cut meat) into the mold then add cheddar-cheese pieces inside, then the piece of wood that hold the brochette and cheddar again. Close the "beef-coat" with your fingers to get a well shaped brochette
Take away the mobile part and push the "squared-brochette" out, you will just have to cook it inside a stove with sweet soja sauce on each face of the meat.

This is a two-piece lawn mower blade balancing fixture. The base is about 4 inches in diameter. It will handle blades with center holes from 3/8" to 1-1/8" diameter in 1/8" increments.

I've included the OpenSCAD file if you want to modify it.

http://www.reprap.org/wiki/Jy-mcu
this code automates setup of bt devices on arduino for jy-mcu bt devices. possibly works on others. anyways what is slick about this is it runs the same port your ramps code would use it on, so when setup, you don't need to remove it. also programs bluetooth device id name, baud rate, and pin number thru arduino serial monitor. just set it for 57600, no ending lines, and it will instruct you what to do next. video here www.youtube.com/embed/WtPqC1PASQY

This isn't a remix but definitely influenced by previous kitchen timer GoPro mods, in particular this one. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:108263

I had a pretty crappy timer to start with which laid on its side and seemed too cumbersome to modify, so took it apart. What I found was the kitchen timer mechanism seems to be almost a standard, after looking online. I had a couple of objectives:

1) Try and keep it as universal as possible.
2) Use the top part to try and protect the mechnism against rain (it will corrode eventually), but this should ensure good operation if used in the rain. Larger top part has a 58mm diameter and the base is 52mm.
3) Make it straight forward to print without support (hence why it's 3 parts).
4) Allow the base to be fixed using any existing GoPro mounting system.
5) Remove the metal outer shell which acts like a bell chamber, as we will use this when camping and have no need for it.

The base part is fixed into place with the 3 small screws, then the other pieces just press together and lock firmly.

I have also made a couple of smaller BASE and TOP parts labelled as BASIC e.g. without the rain shield and reduced the base assembly size, this should cater for other peoples needs.

my H-copter frame is running a APM2.6 FC and it seemed a shame not to be taking advantage of its onboard gimbal stabilization features so I quickly through this design together, printed it, fitted it to my frame and test flew is throughout this morning and I am pleased to inform all it works very well indeed.

the parts are held together with various assorted 2mm screws and bolts I had knocking about but anything not to long (10mm or less in length) and with 2mm thread diameter will do just fine (even the screws that generally come with servo's will suffice).

the servo itself is a Tower-Pro MG995 (Digital Hi-speed) but any similar sized servo will do.

I do advice that you dont use smaller digi servo's as even though their rated for the task they very rarely have the torque to give you nice smooth clean movement, which is what you want on any servo gimbal (also dont use analogue servo's, they just cant keep up with fine movements on a gimbal)

all in all its a very simple concept designed to do one task, namely supply pitch cam stabilization which it does perfectly imho, again Ive used my snap-on/snap-off fitting style so its a 30 second job to swap it out or in if you want to change from the fixed position mount.

description.text:
Note that this part has been superseded by V2 (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:124237)
This is a replacement annular cooling for the Ultimaker nozzle. The original cooling shroud, although functional, can sometimes be counterproductive. The unidirectional nature of the cooling stream can sometimes lift the first layer, especially when printing on a raft. The annular cooling nozzle is aimed at the printed object from all directions, thus cancelling any possible lift.

This is a replacement annular cooling for the Ultimaker nozzle. The original cooling shroud, although functional, can sometimes be counterproductive. The unidirectional nature of the cooling stream can sometimes lift the first layer, especially when printing on a raft. The annular cooling nozzle is aimed at the printed object from all directions, thus cancelling any possible lift.  
The whole assembly is secured under the cooling fan, therefore avoiding contact with the hot aluminium plate which can easily distort PLA part over extended time.  
Make sure to print all parts with flat faces on the platform.  
You will also need the following:  
2x M3x20mm bolts  
2x M3 nuts  
2x M3 PCB spacer  
Align notches and glue all parts using super glue. The use of super glue accelerator is advised.  
File bolt holes using a needle-file to allow M3 bolts to pass through comfartably.  
You may have to untighten the hot end's long screws to rotate the heating block so that it lines up witht the diameter of the nozzle, otherwise the cale of the heating element will interfere.  
Slide assembly in place under the cooling fan through the innermost prodruding long screws.  
Retighten the long screws before securing the assembly in place using 2xM3 PCB spacers. Secure the rest of the assembly to the fan using 2x M3x20mm bolts and nuts.  
The attached photos show the first iteration without the alignment notches.  
I ran the Ultimaker for more than 5 hours printing an object and the nozzle doesn't seem to be afftected by proximity heat from the heating block so far.  
STEP and Autodesk Inventor files included in the ZIP file.  
Enjoy!

This is a phone stand I designed and printed for my own use and that of my coworkers. I went through three iterations of the the design and probably could use one more iteration if I was going to make more (I'd add a shallow box in the base to fill with change for ballast). The current design is simple, rigid, and minimizing print material. I left the name plate space empty so that future printers can add their own details.

The entire design was done in Solidworks. Overall dimensions are h,l,w (5",4",3")

The design objectives were:

fit my phone with the charging cord attached
provide a secure support while using the phone in the dock
ease of printing

One of the design constraints was that the bend radius of most cords is ≈2.5 inch, which is why the phone stand is so tall. This is not an issue on my desk as vertical space is fairly available, while horizontal space is at a premium. I have an Amazon Basics charging cord, which uses the bulkiest connector that I've ever seen and it fits in the 0.5 inch gap just fine.

The first dock I designed used a very bad angle to hold the phone up, it was leaned too far back to be functional. I played around with a few angles after that before settling on 60°. This provides good viewing from a seated position. The first design was a single line similar to a bent paperclip. This iteration looked great, but wouldnt work in PLA without using huge amounts of fill. The stand was too bouncy and was annoying to use the phone in. I added rigidity by supporting the large overhangs.

The other issue with my first design was that the base was too narrow and the phone would tip over if used. I thought about using a wide base for just the phone, but printing would require support material or playing with orientations and overhangs. In the end, I wanted to limit the number of visual features. I planned to lay this on its side and print without any support material. This design prints very cleanly, with only minor issues at the overhang around the charging cable relief.

Dock for a Eleaf iStick 100W TC

The cable may need to be fixed with a small piece of double sided tape.

The slot at the backside is for the cable and to keep the holes for battery ventilation open.
